{
  "The correct order of organs in the GI tract from beginning to end is:": "",
  "Esophagus, mouth, stomach, large intestine, small intestine": "",
  "Stomach, esophagus, mouth, intestine": "",
  "Mouth, pharynx, esophagus, stomach, small intestine, large intestine, anus": "",
  "Pharynx, stomach, esophagus, colon, rectum": "",
  "The gastrointestinal tract is a continuous muscular tube that runs from the mouth through the pharynx, esophagus, stomach, small intestine, and large intestine, ending at the anus.": "",
  "The three parts of the small intestine in order are:": "",
  "Duodenum, jejunum, ileum": "",
  "Jejunum, duodenum, ileum": "",
  "Ileum, jejunum, duodenum": "",
  "Cecum, colon, rectum": "",
  "The small intestine proceeds from the duodenum (shortest, receives bile and pancreatic juice) to the jejunum (primary absorption site) to the ileum (absorbs B12 and bile salts), often remembered as DJ-I.": "",
  "The innermost layer of the GI tract wall is the:": "",
  "Serosa": "",
  "Mucosa": "",
  "Submucosa": "",
  "Muscularis": "",
  "The mucosa is the innermost layer that lines the lumen of the GI tract, and it is responsible for secretion, absorption, and protection against pathogens.": "",
  "How many unique muscle layers does the stomach wall contain?": "",
  "4 (oblique, circular, longitudinal, and diagonal)": "",
  "2 (circular and longitudinal layers only)": "",
  "3 (oblique, circular, and longitudinal)": "",
  "1 (a single circular smooth muscle layer)": "",
  "Unlike most of the GI tract which has two muscle layers, the stomach has an additional oblique layer that allows it to churn and mechanically break down food.": "",
  "Which structure connects the small intestine to the large intestine?": "",
  "Cardiac sphincter": "",
  "Pyloric sphincter": "",
  "Ileocecal valve": "",
  "Lower esophageal sphincter": "",
  "The ileocecal valve is located at the junction of the ileum and the cecum, regulating the flow of chyme from the small intestine into the large intestine and preventing backflow.": "",
  "The outermost layer of most GI tract organs is the:": "",
  "Muscularis (smooth muscle layers)": "",
  "Serosa (visceral peritoneum)": "",
  "Submucosa (connective tissue layer)": "",
  "Mucosa (innermost epithelial lining)": "",
  "The serosa is the outermost layer of intraperitoneal GI organs, consisting of a thin layer of connective tissue covered by mesothelium, and it reduces friction between abdominal organs.": "",
  "Accessory digestive organs include all of the following EXCEPT:": "",
  "Kidneys": "",
  "Pancreas": "",
  "Liver and gallbladder": "",
  "Salivary glands": "",
  "The accessory digestive organs (salivary glands, liver, gallbladder, and pancreas) produce secretions that aid digestion but are not part of the alimentary canal itself. The kidneys belong to the urinary system.": "",
  "The large intestine's primary function is:": "",
  "Chemical digestion of proteins": "",
  "Bile production": "",
  "Water and electrolyte absorption and feces formation": "",
  "Nutrient absorption": "",
  "The large intestine primarily absorbs remaining water and electrolytes from indigestible food residue, compacts the waste into feces, and houses trillions of beneficial gut bacteria.": "",
  "Villi and microvilli are found in the:": "",
  "Small intestine": "",
  "Esophagus": "",
  "Large intestine": "",
  "Stomach": "",
  "The small intestine is lined with finger-like projections called villi and even smaller microvilli on enterocytes, which dramatically increase the surface area available for nutrient absorption.": "",
  "The rectum and anal canal contain which important sphincters?": "",
  "Only the internal anal sphincter": "",
  "Only the external anal sphincter": "",
  "The pyloric and ileocecal sphincters": "",
  "Internal (involuntary smooth muscle) and external (voluntary skeletal muscle) anal sphincters": "",
  "The internal anal sphincter is composed of involuntary smooth muscle that maintains continence at rest, while the external anal sphincter is voluntary skeletal muscle that allows conscious control of defecation.": "",
  "What is peristalsis?": "",
  "The mixing of chyme in the small intestine": "",
  "The release of digestive enzymes into the lumen": "",
  "The voluntary act of chewing food in the mouth": "",
  "Rhythmic, wave-like smooth muscle contractions that propel food along the GI tract": "",
  "Peristalsis consists of coordinated circular and longitudinal muscle contractions that create a wave pushing the food bolus or chyme in an aboral (toward the anus) direction throughout the GI tract.": "",
  "What is the mesentery?": "",
  "The muscular wall of the stomach": "",
  "A sphincter between the stomach and duodenum": "",
  "A double layer of peritoneum that suspends the intestines and carries blood vessels, nerves, and lymphatics": "",
  "A type of digestive enzyme secreted by the pancreas": "",
  "The mesentery is a fan-shaped fold of peritoneum that attaches the intestines to the posterior abdominal wall, providing structural support and serving as a conduit for blood vessels, nerves, and lymphatics.": "",
  "What is the greater omentum?": "",
  "A muscular sphincter in the stomach": "",
  "A segment of the large intestine": "",
  "The lining of the esophagus": "",
  "A large fold of peritoneum that drapes over the intestines like a fatty apron": "",
  "The greater omentum hangs from the greater curvature of the stomach and drapes over the intestines, storing fat, cushioning abdominal organs, and containing immune cells that help fight peritoneal infections.": "",
  "What does the term 'rugae' refer to in GI anatomy?": "",
  "Outpouchings of the colon wall": "",
  "Temporary folds in the stomach lining that allow the organ to expand": "",
  "The finger-like projections in the small intestine": "",
  "The smooth muscle layers of the esophagus": "",
  "Rugae are mucosal folds found in the stomach that flatten out when the stomach fills with food, allowing the organ to stretch and accommodate a large volume of ingested material.": "",
  "What is the enteric nervous system?": "",
  "The vagus nerve branches to the stomach only": "",
  "An intrinsic network of nerve plexuses in the GI wall that independently controls motility, secretion, and blood flow": "",
  "The sympathetic nerves that inhibit digestion": "",
  "The portion of the brain that controls hunger": "",
  "The enteric nervous system, often called the 'gut brain,' contains over 100 million neurons organized into the submucosal (Meissner's) and myenteric (Auerbach's) plexuses, and it can function independently of the central nervous system.": "",
  "What is the lower esophageal sphincter (LES)?": "",
  "The sphincter that controls gastric emptying into the duodenum": "",
  "A ring of smooth muscle at the gastroesophageal junction that prevents gastric acid reflux into the esophagus": "",
  "A valve between the small and large intestine": "",
  "A skeletal muscle sphincter at the top of the esophagus": "",
  "The LES is a physiological sphincter that tonically contracts to keep the gastroesophageal junction closed, preventing acidic stomach contents from refluxing into the esophagus. Dysfunction of the LES leads to GERD.": "",
  "What does the term 'submucosa' refer to?": "",
  "A layer of dense connective tissue beneath the mucosa containing blood vessels, lymphatics, and the submucosal nerve plexus": "",
  "The innermost epithelial lining of the GI tract": "",
  "The outer serous membrane covering GI organs": "",
  "The smooth muscle layer responsible for peristalsis": "",
  "The submucosa lies between the mucosa and the muscularis externa, containing larger blood and lymphatic vessels, glands (in some regions), and the submucosal (Meissner's) nerve plexus that regulates secretions.": "",
  "What is the cecum?": "",
  "A fold of peritoneum supporting the stomach": "",
  "A pouch-like beginning of the large intestine where the ileum empties and the appendix is attached": "",
  "The final portion of the rectum": "",
  "The first part of the small intestine": "",
  "The cecum is a blind-ended pouch located in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen that receives chyme from the ileum via the ileocecal valve and has the vermiform appendix attached to its posteromedial surface.": "",
  "What does the term 'muscularis externa' mean?": "",
  "The connective tissue surrounding the liver": "",
  "The smooth muscle layer of the GI wall composed of an inner circular and outer longitudinal layer responsible for peristalsis": "",
  "A layer of epithelial tissue lining the stomach": "",
  "The voluntary skeletal muscle of the pharynx": "",
  "The muscularis externa consists of two smooth muscle layers — an inner circular layer that narrows the lumen and an outer longitudinal layer that shortens the tube — working together to produce peristaltic contractions.": "",
  "What is the peritoneum?": "",
  "The epithelial lining of the intestinal lumen": "",
  "A large serous membrane that lines the abdominal cavity and covers most abdominal organs": "",
  "The nerve plexus that controls GI motility": "",
  "The peritoneum is the largest serous membrane in the body, with a parietal layer lining the abdominal wall and a visceral layer covering the organs. The peritoneal cavity between them contains a thin film of serous fluid that reduces friction.": "",
  "A 45-year-old patient undergoes abdominal surgery, and the surgeon notes a large, fat-laden membrane draped over the intestines that is walling off a small area of infection. Which structure is serving this protective function?": "",
  "Mesentery": "",
  "Parietal peritoneum": "",
  "Greater omentum": "",
  "Lesser omentum": "",
  "The greater omentum is often called the 'abdominal policeman' because it migrates to areas of infection or inflammation in the peritoneal cavity, walling off the affected area to help contain the spread of infection.": "",
  "A patient with chronic heartburn is diagnosed with gastroesophageal reflux disease. An upper endoscopy reveals damage to the esophageal lining. Which sphincter's dysfunction most likely caused this condition?": "",
  "Lower esophageal sphincter (LES)": "",
  "Upper esophageal sphincter": "",
  "GERD results from incompetence of the lower esophageal sphincter, which allows acidic gastric contents to reflux into the esophagus and damage its squamous epithelial lining, causing inflammation and heartburn.": "",
  "A medical student is examining a cross-section of the jejunum under a microscope. She identifies four distinct layers in the wall. From innermost to outermost, these layers are:": "",
  "Submucosa, mucosa, muscularis externa, serosa": "",
  "Mucosa, muscularis externa, submucosa, adventitia": "",
  "Serosa, muscularis, submucosa, mucosa": "",
  "Mucosa, submucosa, muscularis externa, serosa": "",
  "The four fundamental layers of the GI wall from innermost to outermost are the mucosa (epithelium, lamina propria, muscularis mucosae), submucosa, muscularis externa (circular and longitudinal muscle), and serosa.": "",
  "A patient presents with right lower quadrant abdominal pain. Imaging reveals inflammation at the junction where the ileum meets the large intestine. Which anatomical structure is located at this junction?": "",
  "Ileocecal valve and cecum": "",
  "Sigmoid colon": "",
  "Hepatic flexure": "",
  "The ileocecal valve and cecum are located in the right lower quadrant at the junction of the ileum and large intestine. This is also the area where the appendix is attached, making appendicitis a common consideration for RLQ pain.": "",
  "A surgeon performing a bowel resection notices that when the blood supply to a segment of small intestine is clamped, the tissue supplied by that artery becomes ischemic. The blood vessels reach the intestine through which structure?": "",
  "Serosa alone": "",
  "Rugae": "",
  "The mesentery is a double layer of peritoneum that not only suspends the intestines from the posterior abdominal wall but also serves as the pathway for arteries, veins, lymphatics, and nerves to reach the intestinal wall.": "",
  "A newborn is diagnosed with Hirschsprung disease, in which a segment of the colon lacks nerve cells in the myenteric plexus. This baby will most likely present with which symptom?": "",
  "Diarrhea from excessive peristalsis driven by overactive enteric nerve plexuses in the affected bowel segment": "",
  "Excessive bile secretion from the liver flooding the intestinal lumen and causing malabsorption of dietary lipids": "",
  "Acid reflux into the esophagus due to failure of the lower esophageal sphincter to maintain adequate resting tone": "",
  "Chronic constipation and bowel obstruction due to absent peristalsis in the affected segment": "",
  "Hirschsprung disease involves the congenital absence of ganglion cells in the myenteric (Auerbach's) plexus of the enteric nervous system, resulting in a tonically contracted segment that cannot perform peristalsis, leading to functional obstruction and severe constipation.": "",
  "A patient with celiac disease undergoes a duodenal biopsy that reveals severely flattened structures on the intestinal surface. Which anatomical features are damaged, and why is this clinically significant?": "",
  "Haustra; the patient cannot absorb water": "",
  "Rugae; the patient cannot store food in the stomach": "",
  "Plicae circulares; the patient develops diarrhea from rapid transit": "",
  "Villi and microvilli; the dramatically reduced surface area leads to severe malabsorption of nutrients": "",
  "In celiac disease, the immune-mediated destruction of villi and microvilli in the small intestine drastically reduces the absorptive surface area (normally about 200 square meters), leading to malabsorption of nutrients, vitamins, and minerals.": "",
  "A 60-year-old man is eating a large holiday meal. His stomach expands significantly without a major increase in internal pressure. Which anatomical feature of the stomach allows this accommodation?": "",
  "Haustra": "",
  "Teniae coli": "",
  "Villi": "",
  "Rugae are large mucosal folds in the empty stomach that unfold as the stomach fills, allowing it to expand and hold up to 1.5 liters of food and liquid without a significant rise in intraluminal pressure.": "",
  "During a colonoscopy, a gastroenterologist identifies a polyp in the ascending colon. Anatomically, the ascending colon is located in which region of the abdomen?": "",
  "Midline of the abdomen behind the stomach": "",
  "Right side of the abdomen, running from the cecum upward to the hepatic flexure": "",
  "Left upper quadrant": "",
  "Left lower quadrant near the sigmoid colon": "",
  "The ascending colon runs along the right side of the abdomen from the cecum in the right lower quadrant upward to the hepatic flexure (right colic flexure) near the liver, where it turns to become the transverse colon.": "",
  "A trauma patient has a stab wound to the left upper quadrant of the abdomen. The surgeon discovers a laceration to a retroperitoneal portion of the GI tract. Which organ is most likely injured in this location?": "",
  "Transverse colon": "",
  "Cecum": "",
  "Descending colon": "",
  "The descending colon is a secondarily retroperitoneal organ located in the left side of the abdomen. Unlike the transverse and sigmoid colon which are intraperitoneal and have a mesentery, the descending colon is fixed against the posterior abdominal wall.": ""
}